<p>You claimed your Google Business Profile months ago. You added photos, set your hours, and replied to a few reviews. But your Updates tab sits empty.</p>
<p>That silence costs you visibility. Businesses that post weekly to their Google Business Profile generate 48% more website visits and 34% more direction requests than those that do not post at all. Google treats fresh posts as a relevance signal for <a href="/glossary/local-pack/">local pack</a> rankings and AI Overviews.</p>
<p>This guide breaks down everything about Google Business Profile posts. You will learn what to post, how to write it, which images to use, and how often to publish. We have published 3,500+ blogs and GBP posts across 70+ industries, and this guide covers the exact playbook we follow.</p>
<p><strong>Here is what you will learn:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>The 4 post types and when to use each one</li>
<li>How GBP posts affect your local search rankings</li>
<li>The exact image specs and character limits Google requires</li>
<li>A posting frequency strategy based on your business type</li>
<li>Ready-to-use post templates for 8 industries</li>
<li>Tools that schedule and automate your GBP posts</li>
<li>How to measure whether your posts actually drive results</li>
</ul>
<h2>What Are Google Business Profile Posts?</h2>
<p>Google Business Profile posts are short updates you publish directly to your business listing on Google Search and Maps. They appear below your business info when customers search your name or find you in local results.</p>
<p>Think of them as micro-content for your storefront on Google. Each post can include text, images, videos, and a call-to-action button that links to your website.</p>
<h3>Where GBP Posts Appear</h3>
<p>Your posts show up in 4 places:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Google Search</strong>. In your Business Profile panel on desktop and mobile</li>
<li><strong>Google Maps desktop</strong>. Under your listing details</li>
<li><strong>Google Maps app</strong>. In the Updates tab of your profile</li>
<li><strong>Google business website</strong>. If you use the free Google site</li>
</ol>
<p>Google displays up to 10 of your most recent posts in the Updates section. Anything older than 6 months gets archived.</p>
<h3>How Posts Differ from Reviews and Photos</h3>
<p>Reviews come from customers. Photos can come from anyone. Posts come from you. They are the only content type where you fully control the message, image, and link destination.</p>
<p>That makes posts your best tool for promoting offers, announcing events, and driving traffic to specific pages. If your <a href="/blog/optimize-google-business-profile/">Google Business Profile optimization</a> covers the "what" of your business, posts cover the "what is happening right now."</p>
<h2>The 4 Types of GBP Posts</h2>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="The 4 Google Business Profile post types showing Update, Offer, Event, and Product" src="/images/blog/gbp-post-types.webp" /></p>
<p>Google offers 4 distinct post formats. Each serves a different purpose and displays differently in search results.</p>
<h3>Update Posts (What is New)</h3>
<p>Update posts are the most flexible type. Use them for general announcements, tips, news, behind-the-scenes content, or anything that does not fit the other 3 categories.</p>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Weekly updates, service highlights, team news, blog promotion, seasonal tips.</p>
<h3>Offer Posts</h3>
<p>Offer posts promote discounts, sales, and promotions. They automatically display a "View Offer" button and support coupon codes. Offer posts remain visible until the promotion end date you set.</p>
<p>Research from <a href="https://www.brightlocal.com/learn/google-business-profile-google-posts-updates/">BrightLocal</a> found that Offer posts generate more clicks than any other post type.</p>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Seasonal sales, limited-time discounts, new customer offers, holiday promotions.</p>
<h3>Event Posts</h3>
<p>Event posts promote a specific happening at your business. They require a title plus start and end dates.</p>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Workshops, grand openings, webinars, open houses, seasonal events.</p>
<h3>Product Posts</h3>
<p>Product posts showcase specific items with pricing. They appear in the Products tab of your profile and stay visible until you remove them.</p>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Retail stores, restaurants (menu items), salons (service packages).</p>
