<h2>How GBP Posts Affect Local SEO Rankings</h2>
<p>The honest answer: Google Business Profile posts are not a top-3 ranking factor. Your <a href="/glossary/nap/">NAP</a> consistency, <a href="/glossary/google-reviews/">Google reviews</a>, and website relevance carry more weight. But posts play a clear supporting role that compounds over time.</p>
<h3>The Relevance Signal</h3>
<p>Google's own <a href="https://support.google.com/business/answer/7091?hl=en">documentation on local ranking</a> names 3 factors: relevance, distance, and prominence. Posts feed the relevance signal directly. When you publish a post containing keywords related to your services, Google has fresh text to match against search queries.</p>
<h3>The Activity Signal</h3>
<p>Google rewards active profiles. A profile with weekly posts signals an engaged, operating business. A profile with no posts since 2024 signals neglect. Businesses that started consistent GBP posting saw jumps in <a href="/glossary/local-pack/">local pack</a> rankings within 1 week.</p>
<h3>The Engagement Signal</h3>
<p>Posts drive 3 types of customer actions:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>48%</strong> result in website visits</li>
<li><strong>34%</strong> generate direction requests</li>
<li><strong>17%</strong> trigger phone calls</li>
</ul>
<p>These <a href="/glossary/engagement/">engagement</a> signals feed back into your profile. More clicks, calls, and direction requests tell Google that searchers find your business useful.</p>
<h3>The AI Overview Connection</h3>
<p>In 2026, roughly 40% of local searches trigger AI Overviews at the top of results. Google pulls information from active, well-maintained Business Profiles to populate these summaries. Businesses with recent, keyword-rich posts are more likely to appear in AI Overviews for local queries.</p>
<h3>What Posts Cannot Do</h3>
<p>Posts will not fix a fundamentally broken local SEO strategy. If your NAP data is inconsistent, your categories are wrong, or you have 2 reviews, posting will not save you. Start with the foundations in our <a href="/blog/local-seo-guide/">local SEO guide</a>, then add posts as the next layer.</p>
<h2>How to Write GBP Posts That Get Clicks</h2>
<p>Most GBP posts fail because they read like corporate press releases. The posts that drive clicks follow a simple formula: one point, one image, one action.</p>
<h3>The 3-Part GBP Post Formula</h3>
<p>Every effective post contains 3 elements:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Hook</strong>. First sentence grabs attention with a benefit, stat, or question</li>
<li><strong>Body</strong> ,  2-3 sentences of supporting detail</li>
<li><strong>CTA</strong>. Clear next step with a button</li>
</ol>
<p>Keep total length between 80 and 150 words. Google shows roughly 100 characters before truncating on mobile.</p>
<h3>Keyword Placement</h3>
<p>Include your primary service keyword and city name naturally in the post text. Do not stuff keywords. One mention of each is enough. This supports the relevance signal and aligns with <a href="/blog/seo-content-writing/">SEO content writing</a> best practices.</p>
<p><strong>Weak:</strong> "We are the best dentist. Choose us for dental services."
<strong>Strong:</strong> "Need a same-day dental crown in Portland? Our CEREC technology creates custom crowns in 1 visit. Book online today."</p>
