<td>Thanksgiving, early holiday promotions</td>
<td>Offer, Event</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>December</td>
<td>Holiday closures, new year prep</td>
<td>Update, Event</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>Each month, plan 4 posts minimum: 2 content posts tied to the seasonal theme, 1 offer or promotion post, and 1 post that highlights a recent customer review or outcome. That structure keeps variety without requiring a content strategist.</p>
<h2>GBP Post Audit: 10 Things to Check Before You Publish</h2>
<p>Before hitting publish on any GBP post, run through this checklist. These are the most common mistakes that reduce post performance.</p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] <strong>First sentence delivers a clear benefit or hook</strong> — do not start with your company name</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>City or neighborhood mentioned</strong> at least once in the post body for local relevance</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Primary service keyword included naturally</strong> — one use is enough</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Image is 1,200 x 900 px at 4:3 ratio</strong> — anything else will be auto-cropped</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Post length is 80-150 words</strong> — longer posts get truncated on mobile before the CTA</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>CTA button selected and linked</strong> — never leave the CTA on "None"</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>CTA link goes to a relevant page</strong>, not the homepage</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>UTM parameters added to the link</strong> for GA4 tracking (<code>?utm_source=gbp&amp;utm_medium=post</code>)</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>No restricted content</strong> — no before/after medical claims, no fake offers</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Published day is Tuesday-Thursday</strong> — mid-week posts see 18% higher engagement than weekend posts</li>
</ul>
<h2>What We Learned Publishing 3,500+ GBP Posts Across 70 Industries</h2>
<p>We have published GBP posts at scale for local businesses across industries ranging from dental practices to roofing contractors to martial arts studios. These patterns hold consistently.</p>
<p><strong>The day-of-week effect is real.</strong> Posts published Tuesday through Thursday generate 15-22% more clicks on average than those published Friday through Monday. The working hypothesis: people searching for local services on weekdays have higher intent than weekend browsers.</p>
<p><strong>Offer posts generate 2-3x the clicks of update posts</strong> when the discount is specific (e.g., "$50 off your first AC tune-up") rather than vague ("save this month"). Specificity signals credibility. Vague offers feel like bait.</p>
<p><strong>The first 5 words decide the click rate.</strong> Posts where the first 5 words communicate a specific benefit — not a brand name, not a greeting — consistently outperform those that start with "We are proud to..." or "Welcome to our..." Test: cover the rest of the post and read only the first sentence. Would you keep reading?</p>
<p><strong>Authenticity beats polish.</strong> A real photo taken on a job site, in natural light, with actual equipment and a real technician generates higher engagement than stock photography or branded graphics. The exception: for promotional posts with specific offers, branded graphics with the discount amount displayed visibly outperform photos.</p>
<p><strong>Consistency compounds.</strong> Businesses that post weekly for 6+ consecutive months see a measurable step-change in their local pack rankings compared to those that post in bursts and then go quiet for weeks. Google treats consistent activity as a signal of an operating, reliable business. Inconsistency does the opposite.</p>
<h2>FAQ</h2>
<p><strong>How long do Google Business Profile posts last?</strong></p>
<p>Update posts remain visible on your profile for up to 6 months but lose priority placement after about 7 days. Offer and Event posts stay prominent until their set end date. Product posts remain visible until you manually remove them.</p>
<p><strong>Do Google Business Profile posts help SEO?</strong></p>
<p>Posts support local SEO indirectly. They send relevance signals to Google, increase profile engagement, and provide fresh content that AI Overviews can pull from. They will not single-handedly improve your rankings, but they strengthen your overall <a href="/blog/local-seo-guide/">local SEO</a> strategy when combined with reviews, <a href="/glossary/citation/">citations</a>, and website optimization.</p>
<p><strong>What is the ideal length for a GBP post?</strong></p>
<p>Aim for 80 to 150 words. Google truncates posts at roughly 100 characters on mobile search results. Front-load your key message in the first sentence. The maximum is 1,500 characters, but shorter posts with clear CTAs outperform long ones.</p>
<p><strong>Can I schedule Google Business Profile posts?</strong></p>
<p>Yes. Google added native post scheduling in late 2025. Third-party tools like Publer, SocialBee, and Sendible also support GBP scheduling with bulk posting and analytics.</p>
<p><strong>What image size should I use for GBP posts?</strong></p>
<p>The recommended size is 1,200 x 900 pixels with a 4:3 aspect ratio. Minimum is 400 x 300 pixels. Use JPG or PNG format. Keep file sizes between 10 KB and 5 MB.</p>
<p><strong>How many times per week should I post on Google Business Profile?</strong></p>
<p>At minimum, post once per week to keep your profile active. Service businesses benefit from 1-2 posts per week. Restaurants and retail can post 3-5 times per week. Consistency matters more than volume. See our <a href="/blog/seo-small-business-guide/">SEO for small business guide</a> for how GBP posting fits into a complete strategy.</p>
